message:
Add administrative message filtering and enhanced thread navigation to static viewer

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
OVERVIEW
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

This commit adds sophisticated message categorization and filtering capabilities
to the static viewer, enabling users to distinguish between substantive
conversations and administrative system messages (contact requests, auto-handshakes).
Additionally enhances the thread view with improved UI, search, direct linking,
and richer metadata display.

These changes address the common use case where users want to review actual
conversations without being distracted by system-generated administrative
messages that handle coordination between agents.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
MOTIVATION
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

PROBLEM WITH MIXED MESSAGE TYPES:

In multi-agent systems, there are two distinct types of messages:

1. USER MESSAGES: Actual conversations between agents about work
   - Feature discussions, bug reports, deployment plans
   - Design reviews, code reviews, technical questions
   - Status updates, progress reports

2. ADMINISTRATIVE MESSAGES: System coordination messages
   - Contact requests ("Contact Request from AgentA")
   - Auto-handshake confirmations ("auto-handshake approved")
   - Agent introduction messages
   - Permission grants/denials

When viewing a mailbox with both types mixed together, users typically want to
focus on substantive conversations and filter out the administrative noise.
Previously, there was no way to distinguish or filter these message types.

THREAD NAVIGATION LIMITATIONS:

The previous thread view was functional but lacked:
- Visual thread explorer/picker
- Search within threads
- Thread categorization (all admin vs mixed vs all user messages)
- Direct linking from message detail to thread view
- Thread metadata (importance, latest activity, snippet)

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
CHANGES BY FILE
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ src/mcp_agent_mail/viewer_assets/viewer.js (+197 lines)                    │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
1) ADMINISTRATIVE MESSAGE DETECTION
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

NEW PATTERN DEFINITIONS:

  const ADMIN_SUBJECT_PATTERNS = [
    /^contact request from/i,
    /\bauto-handshake\b/i,
  ];

  const ADMIN_BODY_PATTERNS = [
    /\bauto-handshake\b/i,
  ];

These regex patterns identify administrative messages by matching:

SUBJECT PATTERNS:
- "Contact Request from [AgentName]" - contact request messages
- "auto-handshake" - automatic agent introduction messages

BODY PATTERNS:
- "auto-handshake" - confirmation messages about handshakes

WHY REGEX INSTEAD OF DATABASE FLAG:
Administrative messages aren't explicitly marked in the database schema. They're
identified by content patterns that are consistent across the system. Using
pattern matching allows filtering without schema changes.

WHY CASE-INSENSITIVE:
Different agents or versions might capitalize differently. The /i flag ensures
"Auto-Handshake", "auto-handshake", "AUTO-HANDSHAKE" all match.

NEW METHOD: isAdministrativeMessage(message)

  isAdministrativeMessage(message) {
    const subject = message?.subject || '';
    const snippetSource = message?.snippet ?? message?.body_md ?? '';
    if (ADMIN_SUBJECT_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => pattern.test(subject))) {
      return true;
    }
    if (ADMIN_BODY_PATTERNS.some((pattern) => pattern.test(snippetSource))) {
      return true;
    }
    return false;
  }

ALGORITHM:
1. Extract subject (from message.subject)
2. Extract body text (prefer snippet for performance, fall back to body_md)
3. Test subject against ADMIN_SUBJECT_PATTERNS (any match = true)
4. Test body against ADMIN_BODY_PATTERNS (any match = true)
5. Return false if no patterns match

PERFORMANCE CONSIDERATION:
Uses .some() for early exit - stops testing patterns as soon as one matches.
This is faster than testing all patterns when most messages match the first
pattern.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
2) MESSAGE ENRICHMENT WITH CATEGORIZATION
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

UPDATED: loadMessagesFromDb()

Added fields to SQL query:
  - LENGTH(COALESCE(m.body_md, '')) AS body_length

Enriched message objects with:
  - isAdministrative: boolean flag from pattern matching
  - message_category: 'admin' or 'user' string classification
  - body_length: character count for "Longest First" sorting

  return results.map((msg) => {
    const importance = (msg.importance || '').toLowerCase();
    const bodyLength = Number(msg.body_length) || 0;
    const excerpt = msg.snippet || '';
    const isAdministrative = this.isAdministrativeMessage(msg);

    return {
      ...msg,
      importance,
      body_length: bodyLength,
      recipients: recipientsMap.get(msg.id) || 'Unknown',
      excerpt,
      created_relative: this.formatTimestamp(msg.created_ts),
      created_full: this.formatTimestampFull(msg.created_ts),
      read: false,
      isAdministrative,
      message_category: isAdministrative ? 'admin' : 'user'
    };
  });

WHY ENRICH AT LOAD TIME:
- Categorization happens once per message
- Cached in memory for fast filtering
- Avoids re-running pattern matching on every filter change

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
3) THREAD CATEGORIZATION
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

UPDATED: buildThreads()

Added thread-level categorization based on message composition:

  const adminCount = messages.filter((msg) => msg.isAdministrative).length;
  const hasAdministrative = adminCount > 0;
  const hasNonAdministrative = adminCount < messages.length;
  const threadCategory = hasAdministrative
    ? (hasNonAdministrative ? 'mixed' : 'admin')
    : 'user';

THREAD CATEGORIES:

1. 'user': All messages in thread are user conversations
   - No administrative messages at all
   - Pure conversational thread

2. 'admin': All messages in thread are administrative
   - Example: Contact request → auto-handshake confirmation
   - Pure system coordination thread

3. 'mixed': Thread contains both user and admin messages
   - Example: Contact request followed by actual conversation
   - Real collaboration started with a system handshake

ENRICHED THREAD METADATA:

  threads.push({
    id: thread.thread_key,
    subject: thread.latest_subject || '(no subject)',
    messages: messages,
    last_created_ts: thread.last_created_ts,
    last_created_relative: this.formatTimestamp(thread.last_created_ts),
    message_count: thread.message_count,
    latest_importance: (thread.latest_importance || '').toLowerCase(),
    latest_snippet: thread.latest_snippet || '',
    hasAdministrative,
    hasNonAdministrative,
    thread_category: threadCategory
  });

NEW FIELDS:
- last_created_relative: Human-readable timestamp ("2 hours ago")
- latest_importance: Importance level of most recent message
- latest_snippet: Preview text from latest message
- hasAdministrative: Boolean flag for admin message presence
- hasNonAdministrative: Boolean flag for user message presence
- thread_category: 'user' | 'admin' | 'mixed'

UPDATED: getMessagesInThread()

Also enriches thread messages with categorization:

  return results.map((msg) => {
    const importance = (msg.importance || '').toLowerCase();
    const isAdministrative = this.isAdministrativeMessage({
      subject: msg.subject,
      body_md: msg.body_md,
    });
    return {
      ...msg,
      importance,
      body_length: msg.body_md ? msg.body_md.length : 0,
      isAdministrative,
    };
  });

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
4) MESSAGE TYPE FILTERING
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

NEW FILTER STATE:

  filters: {
    // ... existing filters ...
    messageKind: 'user'  // DEFAULT: Show only user conversations
  }

FILTER OPTIONS:
- 'user': Show only user messages (isAdministrative = false) [DEFAULT]
- 'all': Show all messages (no filtering)
- 'admin': Show only administrative messages (isAdministrative = true)

DEFAULT TO 'user':
Most users want to see conversations, not system messages. Defaulting to 'user'
provides a cleaner initial experience. Users can switch to 'all' to see
everything or 'admin' to audit system coordination.

UPDATED: filterMessages()

Added message kind filtering:

  const messageKind = this.filters.messageKind || 'user';
  if (messageKind === 'user') {
    filtered = filtered.filter(msg => !msg.isAdministrative);
  } else if (messageKind === 'admin') {
    filtered = filtered.filter(msg => msg.isAdministrative);
  }
  // 'all' = no filtering

Also clears selections when filtered messages change:

  if (this.selectedMessage && !filteredIds.has(this.selectedMessage.id)) {
    this.selectedMessage = null;
  }

  if (this.selectedThread && !this.isThreadVisible(this.selectedThread)) {
    this.selectedThread = null;
  }

WHY CLEAR SELECTIONS:
If the user has selected a message/thread and then applies a filter that
excludes it, leaving it selected would be confusing. The UI would show a
selected item that's not in the visible list.

NEW METHOD: isThreadVisible(thread)

Determines if a thread should be visible based on message kind filter:

  isThreadVisible(thread) {
    if (!thread) return false;
    const kind = this.filters.messageKind || 'user';
    if (kind === 'all') {
      return true;
    }
    if (kind === 'admin') {
      return thread.hasAdministrative;
    }
    // 'user' mode
    return thread.hasNonAdministrative;
  }

LOGIC:
- 'all' mode: All threads visible
- 'admin' mode: Show threads with any administrative messages
- 'user' mode: Show threads with any user messages

This means:
- Pure admin threads (hasAdministrative=true, hasNonAdministrative=false)
  → Visible in 'admin' and 'all', hidden in 'user'
- Pure user threads (hasAdministrative=false, hasNonAdministrative=true)
  → Visible in 'user' and 'all', hidden in 'admin'
- Mixed threads (both flags true)
  → Visible in all modes

UPDATED: clearFilters()

Resets messageKind to default 'user':

  clearFilters() {
    this.filters = {
      // ... other filters ...
      messageKind: 'user'
    };
    this.threadSearch = '';
    this.selectedThread = null;
    this.filterMessages();
  }

UPDATED: filtersActive getter

Includes messageKind in active filter detection:

  get filtersActive() {
    return !!(
      this.filters.project ||
      this.filters.sender ||
      this.filters.recipient ||
      this.filters.importance ||
      this.filters.hasThread ||
      this.filters.messageKind !== 'user'  // NEW
    );
  }

WHY CHECK !== 'user':
Since 'user' is the default, it's not considered an "active" filter. Only
'all' or 'admin' show as active filters (highlight the clear filters button).

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
5) THREAD SEARCH AND NAVIGATION
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

NEW STATE:

  threadSearch: '',  // Search query for thread explorer

NEW METHOD: filteredThreads()

Returns threads matching both visibility filter and search query:

  filteredThreads() {
    const query = this.threadSearch.trim().toLowerCase();
    return this.allThreads.filter((thread) => {
      // First check visibility based on message kind filter
      if (!this.isThreadVisible(thread)) {
        return false;
      }
      // If no search query, show all visible threads
      if (!query) {
        return true;
      }
      // Search in subject, ID, and snippet
      const subject = (thread.subject || '').toLowerCase();
      const identifier = (thread.id || '').toLowerCase();
      const snippet = (thread.latest_snippet || '').toLowerCase();
      return subject.includes(query) || identifier.includes(query) || snippet.includes(query);
    });
  }

SEARCH FIELDS:
- Subject: Thread title
- Identifier: Thread ID (e.g., "msg:123", "thread-abc")
- Snippet: Latest message preview

All searches are case-insensitive substring matching.

NEW METHOD: openThreadById(threadId)

Enables direct navigation to a specific thread by ID:

  openThreadById(threadId) {
    if (!threadId) return;
    const normalizedId = String(threadId);
    let thread = this.allThreads.find((t) => t.id === normalizedId);

    // If thread not in allThreads (hasn't been loaded yet), build it
    if (!thread) {
      const messages = this.getMessagesInThread(normalizedId);
      const hasAdministrative = messages.some((msg) => msg.isAdministrative);
      const hasNonAdministrative = messages.some((msg) => !msg.isAdministrative);
      const latestMessage = messages[messages.length - 1];

      thread = {
        id: normalizedId,
        subject: latestMessage?.subject || '(no subject)',
        messages,
        last_created_ts: latestMessage?.created_ts ?? null,
        last_created_relative: latestMessage ? this.formatTimestamp(latestMessage.created_ts) : '',
        message_count: messages.length,
        latest_importance: latestMessage?.importance || '',
        latest_snippet: latestMessage?.body_md?.substring(0, 160) || '',
        hasAdministrative,
        hasNonAdministrative,
        thread_category: hasAdministrative
          ? (hasNonAdministrative ? 'mixed' : 'admin')
          : 'user',
      };

      this.allThreads.push(thread);
    }

    this.selectThread(thread);
    this.threadSearch = '';
  }

ON-DEMAND THREAD BUILDING:
If a user clicks a thread link from message detail, that thread might not be
in allThreads yet (only loaded threads from database are there initially).
This method builds the thread object on-demand from its messages.

WHY CLEAR threadSearch:
Once a thread is selected, clear the search query so the thread view shows
normally without search highlighting.

NEW METHOD: switchToThreadsView()

Switches to threads mode and auto-selects first visible thread:

  switchToThreadsView() {
    this.viewMode = 'threads';
    if (!this.selectedThread) {
      const firstVisibleThread = this.filteredThreads()[0];
      if (firstVisibleThread) {
        this.selectThread(firstVisibleThread);
      }
    }
  }

AUTO-SELECTION:
If no thread is selected, automatically select the first visible one. This
prevents showing an empty thread view when switching modes.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
6) LONGEST FIRST SORTING
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

NEW SORT OPTION: 'longest'

UPDATED: sortMessages()

  case 'longest':
    toSort.sort((a, b) => (b.body_length || 0) - (a.body_length || 0));
    break;

Sorts messages by body_length descending (longest first).

USE CASE:
Users reviewing messages might want to prioritize longer, more detailed
messages (likely to contain important information) over short acknowledgments
or quick replies.

Examples:
- 5000 char detailed design document
- 3200 char bug report with logs
- 150 char "Looks good to me"
- 20 char "Thanks!"

With "Longest First", the design doc and bug report appear first.

